Aldolase B.label: Aldolase B
Aldolase B.description: Aldolase B also known as fructose-bisphosphate aldolase B or liver-type aldolase is one of three isoenzymes of the class I fructose 1,6-bisphosphate aldolase enzyme, and plays a key role in both glycolysis and gluconeogenesis. Wikipedia

Alpha-fetoprotein.label: Alpha-fetoprotein
Alpha-fetoprotein.description:
Alpha-fetoprotein is a protein that in humans is encoded by the AFP gene. The AFP gene is located on the q arm of chromosome 4.
AFP is a major plasma protein produced by the yolk sac and the liver during fetal development. Wikipedia

Calcitonin gene-related peptide.label: Calcitonin gene-related peptide
Calcitonin gene-related peptide.description: Calcitonin gene related peptide is a member of the calcitonin family of peptides, which in humans exists in two forms, α-CGRP and β-CGRP. α-CGRP is a 37-amino acid peptide and is formed from the ... Wikipedia

Binding immunoglobulin protein.label: Binding immunoglobulin protein
Binding immunoglobulin protein.description: Binding immunoglobulin protein also known as 78 kDa glucose-regulated protein or heat shock 70 kDa protein 5 is a protein that in humans is encoded by the HSPA5 gene. Wikipedia

Cannabinoid receptor.label: Cannabinoid receptor
Cannabinoid receptor.description: The cannabinoid receptors are a class of cell membrane receptors under the G protein-coupled receptor superfamily. As is typical of G protein-coupled receptors, the cannabinoid receptors contain seven transmembrane spanning domains. Wikipedia

Cholecystokinin.label: Cholecystokinin
Cholecystokinin.description: Cholecystokinin is a peptide hormone of the gastrointestinal system responsible for stimulating the digestion of fat and protein. Wikipedia

Collagenase.label: Collagenase
Collagenase.description: Used to clean skin ulcers and severe burns.On the skin Side effects - Warnings - How to useInjection Side effects - Warnings - How to use National Library of Medicine
Collagenase.type: Prescription drugConsult a doctor if you have a medical concern.

Cystatin C.label: Cystatin C
Cystatin C.description: Cystatin C or cystatin 3, a protein encoded by the CST3 gene, is mainly used as a biomarker of kidney function. Recently, it has been studied for its role in predicting new-onset or deteriorating cardiovascular disease. Wikipedia

DNA clamp.label: DNA clamp
DNA clamp.description: A DNA clamp, also known as a sliding clamp, is a protein fold that serves as a processivity-promoting factor in DNA replication. Wikipedia

Enkephalin.label: Enkephalin
Enkephalin.description: An enkephalin is a pentapeptide involved in regulating nociception in the body. The enkephalins are termed endogenous ligands, as they are internally derived and bind to the body's opioid receptors. Wikipedia

Enolase 2.label: Enolase 2
Enolase 2.description:
Gamma-enolase, also known as enolase 2 or neuron specific enolase, is an enzyme that in humans is encoded by the ENO2 gene. Gamma-enolase is a phosphopyruvate hydratase.
Gamma-enolase is one of the three enolase isoenzymes found in mammals. Wikipedia

Erythropoietin.label: Erythropoietin
Erythropoietin.description: Erythropoietin, also known as erythropoetin or erthropoyetin or EPO, is a glycoprotein hormone that controls erythropoiesis, or red blood cell production. It is a cytokine for erythrocyte precursors in the bone marrow. Wikipedia
Pregnancy risk: Category C (Risk cannot be ruled out)

Factor IX.label: Factor IX
Factor IX.description: Controls and prevents bleeding episodes in people who have hemophilia B (Christmas disease), including during surgery. This medicine is blood clotting Factor IX.Side effects - Warnings - How to use National Library of Medicine
Factor IX.type: Prescription drugConsult a doctor if you have a medical concern.
Pregnancy risk: Category C (Risk cannot be ruled out)

Gastric inhibitory polypeptide.label: Gastric inhibitory polypeptide
Gastric inhibitory polypeptide.description:
Gastric inhibitory polypeptide, also known as the glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide is a member of the secretin family of hormones.
GIP, along with glucagon-like peptide-1, belongs to a class of molecules referred to as incretins. Wikipedia

Glucokinase.label: Glucokinase
Glucokinase.description: Glucokinase is an enzyme that facilitates phosphorylation of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate. Glucokinase occurs in cells in the liver, pancreas, gut, and brain of humans and most other vertebrates. Wikipedia

Gramicidin.label: Gramicidin
Gramicidin.description: Gramicidin is a heterogeneous mixture of six antibiotic compounds, gramicidins A, B and C, making up 80%, 6%, and 14% respectively, all of which are obtained from the soil bacterial species Bacillus ... Wikipedia

Hydrogen potassium ATPase.label: Hydrogen potassium ATPase
Hydrogen potassium ATPase.description: Gastric hydrogen potassium ATPase is also known as H+/K+ ATPase. Wikipedia

Integrin-linked kinase.label: Integrin-linked kinase
Integrin-linked kinase.description: Integrin-linked kinase is a 59kDa protein originally identified while conducting a yeast-two hybrid screen with integrin β1 as the bait protein. Wikipedia

Lipoprotein(a).label: Lipoprotein(a)
Lipoprotein(a).description: Lipoprotein(a) is a lipoprotein subclass. Genetic studies and numerous epidemiologic studies have identified Lp(a) as a risk factor for atherosclerotic diseases such as coronary heart disease and stroke. Wikipedia

Microphthalmia-associated transcription.label: Microphthalmia-associated transcription factor
Microphthalmia-associated transcription.description: Microphthalmia-associated transcription factor is a basic helix-loop-helix leucine zipper transcription factor involved in melanocyte and osteoclast development. MITF is the most characterized member of the MIT family. Wikipedia

NF-κB.label: NF-κB
NF-κB.description: NF-κB is a protein complex that controls transcription of DNA. NF-κB is found in almost all animal cell types and is involved in cellular responses to stimuli such as stress, cytokines, free radicals, ... Wikipedia

Neprilysin.label: Neprilysin
Neprilysin.description: Neprilysin, also known as membrane metallo-endopeptidase, neutral endopeptidase, cluster of differentiation 10, and common acute lymphoblastic leukemia antigen is an enzyme that in humans is encoded by the MME gene. Wikipedia

Obestatin.label: Obestatin
Obestatin.description: Obestatin is a putative hormone that is potentially produced in the cells lining the stomach and small intestine of several mammals including humans. Wikipedia

P-glycoprotein.label: P-glycoprotein
P-glycoprotein.description: P-glycoprotein 1 also known as multidrug resistance protein 1 or ATP-binding cassette sub-family B member 1 or cluster of differentiation 243 is an important protein of the cell membrane that pumps many foreign substances out of cells. Wikipedia

Pikachurin.label: Pikachurin
Pikachurin.description: Pikachurin, also known as agrin-like protein and EGF-like, fibronectin type-III and laminin G-like domain-containing protein, is a protein that in humans is encoded by the EGFLAM gene. Wikipedia

Prohibitin.label: Prohibitin
Prohibitin.description: Prohibitin, also known as PHB, is a protein that in humans is encoded by the PHB gene. The Phb gene has also been described in animals, fungi, plants, and unicellular eukaryotes. Wikipedia

Ran (biology).label: Ran
Ran (biology).description: Ran also known as GTP-binding nuclear protein Ran is a protein that in humans is encoded by the RAN gene. Ran is a small 25 kDa protein that is involved in transport into and out of the cell nucleus during interphase and also involved in mitosis. Wikipedia

Ryanodine receptor.label: Ryanodine receptor
Ryanodine receptor.description: Ryanodine receptors form a class of intracellular calcium channels in various forms of excitable animal tissue like muscles and neurons. It is the major cellular mediator of calcium-induced calcium release in animal cells. Wikipedia

Streptokinase.label: Streptokinase
Streptokinase.description: Streptokinase is an enzyme secreted by several species of streptococci that can bind and activate human plasminogen. SK is used as an effective and inexpensive thrombolysis medication in some cases of myocardial infarction and pulmonary embolism. Wikipedia

Substance P.label: Substance P
Substance P.description: In the field of neuroscience, substance P is a neuropeptide - a substance that functions as a neurotransmitter and as a neuromodulator. To be specific, substance P is an hendecapeptide - a peptide composed of a chain of 11 amino acid residues. Wikipedia

TGF beta receptors.label: TGF beta receptors
TGF beta receptors.description: TGFβ receptors are single pass serine/threonine kinase receptors. They exist in several different isoforms that can be homo- or heterodimeric. Wikipedia

Thaumatin.label: Thaumatin
Thaumatin.description: Thaumatin is a low-calorie sweetener and flavour modifier. The protein is often used primarily for its flavour-modifying properties and not exclusively as a sweetener. Wikipedia

Transcription factor II H.label: Transcription factor II H
Transcription factor II H.description: Transcription factor II Human is one of several general transcription factors that make up the RNA polymerase II preinitiation complex. TFIIH consists of ten subunits, 7 of which form the core complex. Wikipedia

Urocortin.label: Urocortin
Urocortin.description: Urocortin is a protein that in humans is encoded by the UCN gene. This gene is a member of the sauvagine/corticotropin-releasing factor/urotensin I family. Wikipedia

Aromatase.label: Aromatase
Aromatase.description: Aromatase, also called estrogen synthetase or estrogen synthase, is an enzyme responsible for a key step in the biosynthesis of estrogens. Wikipedia

C-reactive protein.label: C-reactive protein
C-reactive protein.description: C-reactive protein is an annular, pentameric protein found in the blood plasma, the levels of which rise in response to inflammation. Wikipedia

Calcitonin.label: Calcitonin
Calcitonin.description: Calcitonin is a 32-amino acid linear polypeptide hormone that is produced in humans primarily by the parafollicular cells of the thyroid, and in many other animals in the ultimobranchial body. Wikipedia

Myoglobin.label: Myoglobin
Myoglobin.description: Myoglobin is an iron- and oxygen-binding protein found in the muscle tissue of vertebrates in general and in almost all mammals. Wikipedia

Factor VII.label: Factor VII
Factor VII.description: Factor VII is one of the proteins that causes blood to clot in the coagulation cascade. It is an enzyme of the serine protease class. Wikipedia

Nerve growth factor.label: Nerve growth factor
Nerve growth factor.description: Nerve growth factor is a small secreted protein that is important for the growth, maintenance, and survival of certain target neurons. It also functions as a signaling molecule. Wikipedia

Nicotinamide phosphoribosyltransferase.label: Nicotinamide phosphoribosyltransferase
Nicotinamide phosphoribosyltransferase.description: Nicotinamide phosphoribosyltransferase also known as pre-B-cell colony-enhancing factor 1 or visfatin is an enzyme that in humans is encoded by the PBEF1 gene. Wikipedia

Prolactin.label: Prolactin
Prolactin.description: Prolactin, also known as luteotropic hormone or luteotropin, is a protein that in humans is probably best known for its role in enabling female mammals to produce milk however it is influential over a ... Wikipedia

Rhodopsin.label: Rhodopsin
Rhodopsin.description: Rhodopsin, also known as visual purple, is a biological pigment in photoreceptor cells of the retina that is responsible for the first events in the perception of light. Wikipedia

Beta thymosins.label: Beta thymosins
Beta thymosins.description: Beta thymosins are a family of proteins which have in common a sequence of about 40 amino acids similar to the small protein thymosin β4. They are found almost exclusively in multicellular animals. Wikipedia

Integrin.label: Integrin
Integrin.description: Integrins are transmembrane receptors that mediate the attachment between a cell and its surroundings, such as other cells or the extracellular matrix. Wikipedia

Phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase.label: Phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase
Phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase.description:
Phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase is an enzyme in the lyase family used in the metabolic pathway of gluconeogenesis. It converts oxaloacetate into phosphoenolpyruvate and carbon dioxide.
It is found in two forms, cytosolic and mitochondrial. Wikipedia

ANKRD2.label: ANKRD2
ANKRD2.description: Ankyrin repeat domain-containing protein 2 is a protein that in humans is encoded by the ANKRD2 gene. Wikipedia

Ecotin.label: Ecotin
Ecotin.description: In molecular biology, ecotin is a protease inhibitor which belongs to MEROPS inhibitor family I11, clan IN. Wikipedia

Heat shock factor.label: Heat shock factor
Heat shock factor.description: Heat shock factor, in molecular biology, is the name given to transcription factors that regulate the expression of the heat shock proteins. A typical example is the heat shock factor of Drosophila melanogaster. Wikipedia
